Sep 22 2008 	Away From The Strip	Set in a pleasant residential area of west Las Vegas, the Suncoast is a well-kept hotel/casino catering to frequent Las Vegas visitors who have tired of the endless traffic and construction noise of The Strip. (The Bellagio, for example, seems to be surrounded by sprouting high-rises topped by giant cranes.)The rooms are spacious and well-appointed, with wall-to-wall, floor-to-ceiling windows. Request the golf course side and you will be rewarded with a panoramic view of the greens, as well as the small pool area of the hotel.Though our room was beginning to show some signs of use (stains on sofa and chair), it was kept spotlessly clean by the housekeeping staff.The Suncoast also provides visitors with movie theatres and a bowling alley - but, disappointingly, no spa.Parking is plentiful and the lot well lit. There is a shuttle bus to the Orleans and the Gold Coast. I'm not sure about the other Boyd properties.The players cards are being updated to include all of the Boyd casinos which include the above as well as the California, Sam's Town and Main Street.Though we qualified for the casino rate, this was still high compared to other Coast hotels. The Suncoast does have seasonal specials which are good value and worth signing up for their e-mails.Across the street from the Suncoast is a brand new, low-rise, mega-shopping center complete with upscale stores and restaurants. The Red Rock Casino is just a short drive away.We can recommend the buffet, with a good selection of freshly prepared food. The breakfast buffet was provided with our room. The casino and hotel staff were pleasant and courteous. Beverage service was prompt. We would recommend the Suncoast to those who have &quot;done&quot; the strip and are not afraid to drive around Las Vegas.	
Aug 24 2008 	Sunny at the Suncoast!	Stayed two nights at The Suncoast as a friend and I were attending a party in the Summerlin area. Since it opened, we’ve always played at Red Rocks, but that hotel is way too expensive for our liking. By staying at the Coast, we’d be located near our friend’s house and also near our favorite casino. It is imperative to have a car when staying this far from the Strip, but we never miss the hustle, bustle, and traffic of the Strip, either, when staying in Summerlin.The room at Suncoast was huge: king sized bed, sofa, flat screen tv, separate vanity area with two sinks, the bathroom had a shower/tub with lots of hot water, and w.c. The bed was comfortable enough, though the pillows were awful.The maid came fairly early in the day, which is always nice. The room was spotless and the amenities were replenished on the second day.Had no problem on the hotel end, but there was a major sabotage: My friend had booked a table for dinner on Saturday night in Primo’s months before our trip – we were to have her birthday dinner there. When she called the hotel on Wednesday to reconfirm her room and dinner reservation, she was informed that Primo’s was closed for renovations. It’s unconscionable that a restaurant would NOT call a customer to inform that person that the place would be closed. I managed to get a table at the wonderful Silverado in The South Pointe, but that should not have had to happen.We did have great bagels at the Bagel Cafe Express. I’m Jewish and know a good bagel; trust me, the bagels are well worth it!I would definitely stay here again, though I’d bring my own pillow!	
Aug 22 2008 	Nice place bad beds!	A friend &amp; I were going out to Las Vegas for a long weekend in August. We wanted to stay in the Summerlin area because we were attending a friend's party, and our friend did not live too far from the Suncoast. I was a little hesitant to stay at the Suncoast due to some of the previous reviews on Trip Advisor regarding the bad beds &amp; poor pillows.The friend that I was going with and I discussed it and we decided to give the Suncoast a try anyways. I mean, how bad could a bed be, right?A couple of weeks before our trip I called the Suncoast &amp; spoke to the hotel manager regarding my concerns about the hotel's beds. She assured me that the mattresses had all been replaced about 1.5 years ago and that the pillows were fine.After speaking with her, I felt better &amp; decided to stay there.I think the manager must have put a note in my reservation, because when I checked in to the Suncoast I got upgraded to the most amazing 1700 sq foot suite, a Tuscany Suite.This Suite was fabulous - foyer with 1/2 bath, separating a huge living room and a good sized bedroom with absolutely the biggest jacuzzi bathtub I have ever seen in my life! Floor to ceiling windows in all rooms of the suite, a walk in shower big enough for 6 people and a beautiful looking bed.I don't mean to harp on the bed but a good night's sleep is very important to me, and a comfortable mattress &amp; feather (or at least fluffy) pillows are quite necessary.Well, sorry to say, the reviewers were right and I had the 3 worst nights of sleep in any hotel I have ever stayed in. The bed was SO uncomfortable that I woke up every morning with a very sore back. It was so bad that I could have used a chiropractor! The pillows were horrible foam rubber ones and not a feather pillow was to be found in the entire hotel. One would think that especially a suite would have the most comfortable bed imaginable and scads of feather pillows.Sorry folks -not at the Suncoast!!I was also very surprised that the suite didn't offer more &quot;treats&quot; such as slippers, bathrobes, upgraded bath amenities, bottled water or anything. During my 3-night stay things that got used (pads of paper, shampoo, etc) were not replaced. My friend stayed in a regular room and the beds &amp; pillows were the same as in the suite. The standard rooms were beautiful - very spacious &amp; comfortable with a couch &amp; coffee table, and a separate double sink area from the shower &amp; toilet area.The staff were very friendly &amp; accommodating, The casino wasn't lucky for me but I just go to have fun &amp; play the penny slots.The hotel and casino itself were very nice and the Bagel Cafe Express has the best everything bagels I've ever tasted,but until I know that the hotel has improved on their bedding I will never stay there again!	
