Jul 24 2007 	Surprised at how lovely the rooms were!	We have family that lives near this hotel and have eaten at the cafe several times. We have always been pleased with the food and service in the cafe. On this trip we found ourselves in need a hotel room for 1 night. We choose the Suncoast because of the low price and close proximity to our family. When we arrived in the rooms I was so surprised at how lovely they were. They have possibly been remodeled recently. We had 2 rooms, one on the 3rd floor and one on the fourth floor. In comparision to most hotels the rooms were quite spacious. The rooms had large flat screen T.V's and granite countertops in the bathrooms. The bathroom was two rooms with the shower and toliet separate from the vanity and sink. The room included a iron and ironing board. On the downside no coffee maker in the room. Of the two rooms, the room facing the pool had very nice views and the room on the opposite side had a boring view. The website I booked the room through gave us free breakfast in the buffet. I'm glad it was free because it was not very good! I would not eat there again.	
Jul 21 2007	Good hotel for the money but needs improvement	I had a decent stay here. I love the location -- nowhere near the Strip or Downtown (but you could get to either in 20 mins by car), close to Red Rock Canyon. What a treat to look out the window and see golf courses and mountains instead of more hotel towers and neon lights.The room was huge, clean, nicely furnished, but (oddly) had very little light available at night. Floor to ceiling windows make it very bright and cheery by day, but there are just a few dim lamps in the room. Strange.Large plasma TV with an OK selection of stations. Internet connection was advertised but mine didn't work. The &quot;technician&quot; they sent up to help was useless - barely knew what a computer was.Other amenities? Fitness room was adequate, nothing more. No steam room, spa, etc., which I missed. Swimming pool was OK, but nothing to write home about.Food ranged from so-so to pretty good. The buffet was a notch or two below average for Vegas. The coffee shop was blah. They have some good graveyard specials (on paper at least) but I didn't try them. The food in the Italian restaurant was just OK. On the other hand, Primo's (the steakhouse) was fabulous -- excellent food, superb room, good prices. One of the best meals I've had in Vegas ever.They seem to have all the bases covered when it comes to gambling, but service is rocky. One night I sat down at a blackjack table, put $100 down and asked for change, but the dealer just kept on dealing and never cut me into the game. So I walked away. Complained to the pit boss but she didn't seem too concerned. Guess stuff like that happens a lot. Service in other parts of the casino was similarly spotty. Do they want our money or not?Poker room was good, but I like the one at the Orleans better -- more atmosphere (maybe because it's older).This place definitely draws the geriatric crowd. I arrived on Monday and not until Thursday night did I see any appreciable number of people under 50, and even then it was mostly seniors.This place provides a good base of operations if you want to be away from the Strip and choose your forays there for yourself. It's also very close to the new Red Rock Casino, which is spectacular but four times the price. Stay at the Suncoast, hang at the Red Rock, and you'll have a great time.	
