Dec 19 2006 	A good choice if you don't mind being away from the Strip	My wife and I stayed here in mid-December, 2006 for a weekend getaway from Los Angeles. Everything was wonderful. Here is a quick rundown from beginning to end:1) Check-in on a Sat. afternoon was quick and smooth. One issue is that the registration desk is in the heart of the casino. We parked in a side parking lot(closest to the 95 freeway exit) and had to lug our bag thru the whole casino. I did not see any bellman but then again, we didn't look for one either. 2) All employees we had contact with were very polite. When we used the credit card to check-in, they asked for id. Since we were once a victim of identity theft, we appreciate it more these days. 3) The room we had was quite large, 550 square feet. We had a king-bed. The room had a flat screen tv. Note if you bring kids, the channel choices are pretty much limited to news and sports. We had a table, plenty of outlets, a sofa and the bathroom was huge. It has two sinks and the toilet/shower area has a sliding door to separate it. One little nicety for the wife was that the hairdryer located in the room was more powerful than the standard tiny ones most motel chains have. The view was not important to us but we did have a nice one overlooking a golf course and mountains. Overall, the room was clean, spacious, and the weekend rate of $150(163 with tax) may be high for Vegas but I have paid a lot more for the same or less in or out of Vegas. The only negative I can think of was the lighting. There are just a few tiny lamps so don't lose a contact lense!! 4) We ate breakfast and dinner in the coffee shop, Cafe Siena. The food quality was decent though the time between ordering the food and getting it in front of you seemed slow. Service seemed fine and the timing may just have been due to the kitchen since both meals seemed slow in coming but fortunately, the food was still hot! 5) As my wife plays just slots and I spend my time in the race/sports book, the smallish casino suited our needs just fine. If you like to &quot;float&quot; around, this casino may not be the best choice for you. 6) The jacuzzi area was nice and towels are provided. 7) Though I would not say this hotel promotes bringing the kids with you(there are &quot;warning&quot; signs posted to tell you if they see a kid, an adult better be attached to them) , there is a movie theatre, bowling area, and ice cream parlor to keep them occupied. The pool is small so maybe not best if you come in the summer and they want to do a lot of splashing/diving. 8) As has been mentioned in previous reviews, this hotel is about 12+ miles from the heart of the strip. I suggest having a car but the hotel does have a shuttle that takes you to a sister property towards the south part of the strip, The Barbary Coast. There is a Marriott hotel next door with a small casino in it called Rampart if you need a variety. It probably is about a 10 minute walk from door-to-door.9)Check out at the desk was a breeze. You do have the option of checking out via the tv. We enjoyed our stay here and my thoughts are if you don't need the strip or don't mind driving, can accept paying more than Circus Circus rates, and want a good-sized, quiet room, give this place a try.	
