Aug 27 2005	Never felt so deceived by reviews	I am not writing to complain. I am writing to warn off trusting readers from believing these raving reviews for Suncoast. I have used Trip Advisor for years; I swear by it, and travel no where without consulting it. But I now feel, in retrospect, utterly deceived by these rave reviews for the Suncoast resort. On the strength of them, I booked us in for our wedding anniversary. Ouch! The litany of our woes began: no one came to help us with our bags when we first drove up. Our $240 a night room was very ordinary. (For example, no in-room safe -- a staple in every hotel i've ever stayed at). Dinner service at Primo's was bad, bad, bad; and took forever for us to be waited on, despite a half-empty restaurant; food was tasteless. Slot machines give paper tickets, no coins drop when you win (a trend in Las Vegas I wasn't aware of). Since there was no in-room safe; the next morning I tried to leave my laptop with personnel inside the security cage; they said they had no boxes to rent, nor could they take responsibility for the computer; as I am writing a book and the laptop had files on it I couldn't afford to have anyone read or steal, I was left to lug it around the Strip all day. Incidentally, it took a far longer time to get downtown from the Summerlin area to the Strip, than the reviews said.Decided I'd had enough. went on the Internet to Trip Advisor, learned the Venetian resort had a king luxury suite with sunken living room at $169 a night, or $70 less than the Suncoast. Booked it. Checked out of Suncoast at 7 p.m. and into the Venetian. Three bellmen surrounded our car when we drove up to the Venetian; whisked our bags inside. Gorgeous classical music playing. Breath-taking decor and art along the walk between registration desk and the main hotel. Our room was stunning; beautiful antiques and classy decorations - - and Vivaldi!! In-room safe that easily stored my lap-top. Helpful concierge that stayed on the phone 15 minutes gettting us tickets to a late night show (Jubilee!). Slots produced coins dropping into the tray whenever you won. Just like the old days. (I'm into nostalgia, especially on a fantastic anniversary!) Heaven! I'll go back to the Venetian in a minute.Every resort will appeal to some people. I know there is a (heavy) market for the Suncoast - - to the dismay of the near-by Marriott's. The $52 a night rooms appeal to families, and the gambling tables are inexpensive. I just think that the visitor weighing whether to stay there or not, needs to be told (as I have attempted here) that the overwhelming ''raves&quot; here for the Suncoast are deceiving. It is a clean, inexpensive large hotel, way out of town. Period.	
Aug 26 2005	Definitely a very good hotel for the money	Pros: $52/night (weekdays), fairly large rooms, nice golf course/mountain view (be sure to ask for it upon check-in), very nice bathrooms with dual sinks/marble counters/large &quot;earth&quot;-tiled side walls/strong water power, free breakfast buffet every morning (given free vouchers upon check-in).Cons: 3rd night stay could smell smoke coming through A/C vents, tap water not very good tasting, bath towels VERY full of loose LINT, &quot;Therapeutic Thursday&quot; pool party VERY loud until 10:30pm (baby crying through the night).Overall this hotel is very good and should get the high marks most people give it. Also, it is close to some nice shopping and restaurants (e.g., Cheesecake Factory, ClaimJumper, Chilis, Roy's Hawaiian Fusion, etc.). We drove out to Red Rock Canyon for some calm and quiet and it was beautiful, and only a 15 minute drive from the hotel. The strip is about a 20-25 minute drive. Would we stay again? Probably not but will be open to trying the new SouthCoast Hotel when it opens in early 2006. This hotel is just south of the strip and closer for us Los Angeles folks. At day's end, I do recommend this hotel but with some reservation.	
