Aug 4 2005	Best kept secret in Las Vegas!	Beautiful property, large, clean rooms with ***cold*** air conditioning (you'll want that in the desert!), staff extremely friendly and helpful, absolutely wonderful restaurants, casino extremely clean (don't know how they do it, it never closes, of course) just like the rest of the hotel. We had a room on the casino side and although you can see the (clean) roof of the casino, you also have a million dollar view of Las Vegas, especially at night when the city sparkles. No request was too much for any of the staff in any department. I've never seen such clean rooms. The decor is tasteful and modern. Perhaps best of all, it's NOT on The Strip. We visited a few casinos on The Strip and let me tell you I was glad we were staying at Suncoast. It felt like coming home when we returned to our room. We were sorry to have to leave but will definitely come back. Be sure to get the Club Card for the slots. Even with a little playing the points add up fast and we used them to get a great free meal. We ate almost all meals at Suncoast and they were all delicious. Don't miss the rasberry iced tea, it's the best in the world. We don't have children but there are services dedicated to them as well. They won't feel left out. Explore the property. It's large (how they fit a 64-lane state of the art bowling alley on the 2nd floor and made it so quiet you wouldn't know it's there, I don't know), but it's not ridiculously large and irritating like so many hotels on The Strip. We can't wait to go back next year. THANK YOU, SUNCOAST!	
Jul 25 2005	The best kept secret !	After weighing out the comments, I decided to go in favor of the good reviews and ignore the bad ones for many reasons. I arrived thurs at the Suncoast and I must say, for $50 I have found the &quot;Golden Goose&quot;.Whoever said the Suncoast was too smokey, needs to stay at the Holiday Inn (no casino). I'm not a smoker myself, however I am mature enough to accept that the by-product smoke goes along with the scheme of things.I didn't read anyone complaining about the free drinks or the half naked waitresses passing them out (the true smokescreen).There is a reason they call it &quot;Sin City&quot;. Who cares about not getting the &quot;Golf course view&quot;, Tiger Woods ain't out there waiving at me. The 550sq ft. room was not only sufficient, it was decorated beautifully; I closed the curtains and enjoyed-That View. Although me and my husband ate bkfst with the free coupons, the buffet is only $5.95, who expects &quot;delicious delicacy&quot; for under $6 anyway?The front desk staff were handing out coupon books and free buffet tickets &quot;Hand over Fist&quot;, who cares if it don't taste like your mamma's cooking.I took my kids bowling with the coupons, and we saw the &quot;Fantastic 4&quot; at the theatre (free popcorn coupon).For the &quot;Goldilocks&quot; looking for the cleanest air, the orthopedic mattress, the gorgeous view, and cuisine meals, all at the best price: &quot;Stay at Home&quot;.For those of us looking for the best kept secret: try the Suncoast.I want to thank the tripadvisor for being a great tool when it comes to vacation planing. you are also a &quot;Golden Goose&quot;.	
Jul 19 2005 	Better than expected!	Just returned from a 4 night stay at the Suncoast in Las Vegas. We usually stay at the JW Marriott which is located right next to the Suncoast but they didn't have rooms available so we thought we'd try the Suncoast. I have to say that we were really impressed all around. The price: We booked online directly through the Suncoast's website. The room rate we got was $59 a night and included breakfast buffet for 2, 2 passes to the pool party, and coupon book with discounts on ice cream, coffe, free popcorn at the movie theatre, bowling, golf coupons and many more. For $59 a night we really wondered about the quality of the room we were going to get. What a surprise!The room: Located on a non-smoking floor, very nice! The rooms are large by Vegas standards. We had a room with 2 double beds - very comfortable by the way , a comfy chair and ottoman, a table with 3 chairs, armoire with TV, and a desk with chair. We were traveling as a family of 4, 2 adults, 2 toddlers. We had plenty of room and never felt cramped. The bathroom is mid sized, with a sliding door that seperates the sink/vanity area from the toilet/shower area. Soaps, shampoos, bath gel, and a hair dryer were availble too. I didn't include an inside picture of the room, if you go to the Suncoast website you'll see exactly what our room looked like, same bedding, decor, etc. It was very nice. The floor to ceiling windows really give the room a nice open feel. We had a great view of the golf course, pool, and the JW from our room. In comparison to the JW rooms, the only difference is that the bathroom is larger. The room itself is actually nicer at the Suncoast and at a 3rd of the price it's a great deal!Service: Excellent - Valets, bell services, room service, pool servers, front desk, security, everyone we came into contact with was exceptionally nice!Food: The prices here for food are excellent, very reasonable! Tried the Mexican restaurant for lunch one day, pretty good food! The bill for 3 adults and 2 toddlers was just over $25 with entrees, and drinks! Prices are great, espcially the lunch specials! We also had ice cream at the ice cream shop, huge sundaes for just $4, got 2 for 1 with the coupon book! Had a few pastries from the coffe place too, very good! Room Service prices are the best i've ever seen. They state that there is a service charge of $2 per person, but we were never charged more than $2 total, even when ordering for a group of 7 down by the pool. Full american breakfast - eggs, bacon, toast, hash browns - $7.95, cereal $2.95, pancakes - 4 of the biggest we've seen, just $4.95. We also had room service by the pool one afternoon - Chicken fingers and fries - enough for 2 to share $8.95, soft drinks $2.00 - and they don't just bring a can or one single cup, they bring a carafe full of soda and ice and a cup for each, you get about 3 full drinks from each. Again, across the way at the JW you'll pay double to triple the price for room service and there is no difference in quality, I think the food at the Suncoast was actually better!Pool: It's not a very big pool, but that's ok because it was never crowded while we were there. One morning we went down at 9am to swim and there were never more than 3 or 4 other people in the pool with us. We stayed down there until 2pm and we're alone half of the time. There's also a seperate jaccuzi up some steps on it's own patio. The first day we arrived the pool was so warm that the kids didn't even want to swim, by the next morning the temp was nice and cool.Casino: SMOKEY!!!! When we initially pulled up to the casino you could smell the smoke as we got out of the car, luckily we either got use to it or the filters started working a little better because it didn't seem so bad by day 2! We don't really gamble, slots here and there, but the casino looked nice, wasn't too crowded, and was a mix of young and old. The resort also has a movie theater, bowling alley, a kids club, and some other restaurants which we didn't try. I would definetly stay here again, my husband and I agreed that the Suncoast is better than the JW in all respects except for the pool (the pool at the JW is fantastic!). Great rooms, good inexpensive food, lots of food choices. The Suncoast is also located near a few shopping centers where you'll find a Cheesecake Factory, Claim Jumper, Mimi's, Chili's, and PF Changs. You'll be about 20-30 minutes to the strip depending on traffic, oh yes there is traffic! It's traffic comporable to LA and Orange County, the freeways are a mess! If anyone tries to get you to use the beltway, ignore them, it's worse than the freeway traffic! I would recommend the Suncoast for families, younger people who aren't party animals, and older folks. If you're a partier this isn't the place for you, you belong on the strip!	
Jul 14 2005	A Terrific Place to Stay	My wife and I have stayed at many hotels in Vegas over the past 30 years and I have to say that the SunCoast ranks up as the best overall. We stayed 3 nights (Sun - Tues) 4 days and it was one of the best trips to Vegas we have had. The hotel is in a great part of town - Summerlin. It is one of the newer areas in Las Vegas surrounded by great shopping malls and Restaurants. It is a mixed residential/business area but definitely upper class area.The Hotel is very attractive from the outside with lots of self parking or you can use the valet service as we did. We found the casino to be plenty big but not so big that you get lost in it. We checked in quickly and went to our room; a nice size room with floor to ceiling windows that overlooked the Badlands golf course.....what a view!!! The room was very clean and nicely decorated (as well as any Vegas hotel can be). I called the bell desk for our luggage and within 3 minutes it was at our room.We found the service to be good from everyone and found the staff to be friendly and efficient. The hotel has just about everything you want - plenty of gaming, a variety of food, a nice movie theater, pool and spa (guess one drawback might be that the pool is not very big), a gym, hair salons, etc. In regards to the food, I had read several posts here regarding the poor quality of the food. On Monday night, we went up to the strip and paid $22 for the buffet at Ceasars Palace. On Tuesday night we ate at the Suncoast Buffet for $13 and found it to be much better than Ceasars. We also ate a breakfast buffet and ate at the coffee shop and found both to be very good. No complaints from me on the food. They also have a Seattles Best Coffee bar and an ice cream stand which I enjoyed. They also have a great bowling alley.If you are looking for the exciting night life and crowds of the strip, this is not the place. But it is not boring either. We found the crowd to be mixed age and somewhat like you might find on the strip and not the old locals that you find at some of the off strip casinos. My biggest disappointment was that they did not have a poker room as I enjoy playing.For those of you that care, they have some of the best looking cocktail waitresses I've seen in Vegas. If you have seen the ones at the Rio then these girls are just as attractive.Best of all, we went home with more money than we came with. Lots of video poker machines - more than I have seen in most casinos. No Let it Ride tables though. Table minimums for blackjack were mostly $5. Its about a 30 minute drive up to the strip with traffic so that can be a drawback, but if you get to the strip like we did and grow tired of the crowds, its so nice to get back to the Suncoast. We have definitely found a new place to stay in Las Vegas. Looking forward to our next trip.	
Jun 27 2005	Really Outstanding!	The Suncoast is out there, off the beaten path but it's really worth the drive. The rooms are huge, as well as the bathrooms. They were also spotless. There are a variety of restaurants. (Go hungry to the Mexican restaurant---the chips and salsa w/beans will fill you up!) I was able to get a room for four days during the week at $51.00 per night on the 'net. Prices go up considerably on Friday night but still, rent a car, don't stay on the strip. You will not believe how relaxing this place is. The view of the surrounding mountains was incredible. You do not appreciate Nevada unless you get away from Las Vegas. Also this hotel is only about 12 miles or so, if that, from Red Rocks which is awesome. Also, a big point is that we do not gamble so the slots, etc., meant nothing to us. The bartenders were great. Only downside, hotel registration does NOT give good directions and isn't particular pleasant. The housekeepers were often frowning. Possibly too much work. A good tip helped. The parking valets were smiling and happy to help and pool was beautiful and empty in the morning and evening. The casino is smokey, but that's pretty much the case anywhere you'd go. My kids are 13 and 16 and they loved it. Because we booked for four days (through Expedia) we received breakfast every morning. The buffet was just above average but don't expect to get an incredible meal here. Go elsewhere if you are vacationing strictly for the food. The upscale restaurant (Primo's) had average service, good prime rib and fabulous chicken. But it was no place for teenagers who were picky eaters. I did think the cost of the room service was very reasonable as well.	
